Based on your console.log() we can see that you are using **old** Http, please update to using `HttpClient`. `Http` has been deprecated for ages! You can refer to the documentation: [`HttpClient`][1]

&lt;!-- language-all: lang-ts --&gt;

But in short.... So remove `HttpModule` and `Http` and replace those with `HttpClientModule` and `HttpClient`.

In app module:

    import { HttpClientModule } from &#39;@angular/common/http&#39;;
    
    // ....
    
    imports: [
      //...
      HttpClientModule
    ]

create an interface (or class), since you should type your data:

    // name interface how you want
    export interface Examene {
      id: number;
      nombreExa: string;
      // rest of properties here!
    }

In your service:

    import { catchError } from &#39;rxjs/operators&#39;;
    import { Observable } from &#39;rxjs&#39;;
    import { HttpClient } from &#39;@angular/common/http&#39;;

    // ....

    constructor(private httpClient: HttpClient) { }

    getOneExamen(id): Observable&lt;Examene&gt; {
      return this.httpClient.get&lt;Examene&gt;(&#39;....&#39;).pipe(
        catchError(...)
      )
    }

and then component:

    selectedExamen = &lt;Examene&gt;{};

    examenClicked(exa) {
      this.dataService.getOneExamen(exa.id).subscribe(
        (data: Examene) =&gt; {
          // with httpClient we don&#39;t need to parse json, so this works with HttpClient!
          this.selectedExamen = data; 
          console.log(&#39;JSON DATA ---&gt;&#39;, data); 
        },
        error =&gt; {
          console.log(error);
        }
      );
    }

BUT
---

If you are using a reaaaaally old version of angular and have to use `Http` for some reason, you are missing `data.json()` from your code, that&#39;s why it doesn&#39;t work as expect. Before `HttpClient` we needed to parse the json from response, but HttpClient does that for us now. So in that case your code should look like:

    this.selectedExamen = data.json();


